## TypeScript

- ALWAYS use `<script lang="ts">` in `.svelte` files.
- Type props inline inside the `$props()` destructuring or with a named type.
- Use `.svelte.ts` (not `.ts`) for modules that use runes (`$state`, `$derived`, etc.) outside components.
- Import types from `svelte` as needed: `Snippet`, `Component`, etc.

---

## SvelteKit Conventions

- `+page.svelte` / `+layout.svelte` — route components.
- `+page.ts` / `+layout.ts` — universal `load` functions (run on server AND client).
- `+page.server.ts` / `+layout.server.ts` — server-only `load`, `actions`.
- `+server.ts` — API endpoints (`GET`, `POST`, etc.).
- Import `$app/navigation`, `$app/stores`, `$app/environment` for SvelteKit utilities.
- In `+layout.svelte`, the child route is rendered via the `children` snippet: `{@render children()}`.
- Access load data via `$props()`:

```svelte
<!-- +page.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import type { PageData } from './$types';
  let { data }: { data: PageData } = $props();
</script>
```

---

## Styling — Tailwind CSS 4

- Use Tailwind utility classes directly in markup.
- This project uses `tailwind-merge` and `clsx` for conditional class composition.
- Use `tailwind-variants` for component variant styling.
- NEVER use `<style>` blocks for things Tailwind handles. Only use `<style>` for truly custom CSS (animations, complex selectors, third-party overrides).

